TAINTED DRUG - USA (02): INJECTIBLE ARTHRITIS GEL, METHYLOBACTERIUM
*******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Tue 19 Dec 2017
Source: Sanofi Genzyme Device Recall Update Notice [edited]


This notice identified the contaminant:
"....an ongoing investigation revealed the presence of _Methylobacterium thiocyanatum_, an alpha proteobacterial class, aerobic Gram negative rod. The microbe is a common airborne organism and is a rare cause of human infections. The species can cause infection in both immunocompromised and immunocompetent patients. Sensitivity analysis is still pending.

A literature search suggests that _Methylobacterium spp_ are susceptible to amikacin, gentamicin, ciprofloxacin (see below) and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole and have various levels of susceptibility to the beta-lactam antibiotics (due to beta-lactamase production) with high sensitivity to ceftriaxone, ceftrizoxime and imipenem. However, the drug resistance patterns suggest that _M. thiocyanatum_ are resistant to aztreonam and ciprofloxacin. Antibiotic sensitivities of the _M. thiocyanatum_ isolated from Synvisc-One lot 7RSL021 are being determined at present.

This recalled lot was distributed in the USA between 25 Oct 2017 and 7 Nov 2017.

--
