******
[2]
Date: Fri 5 Jan 2018
Source: EpiCore Global Surveillance Project [edited]


Several variables were noted in some areas: People were affected by change of climate ad weather; cold/warmth could trigger some response pain in joints, possibly people were subject to arthritis and other muscle/joint diagnoses lately.

I've seen several cases of visible inflammation along with cuts and or a harsh bruising, also with patients describing as pain around joint regions. I would not rule out common dermatology issues.

Could this possibly be a result of an allergic reaction triggered when a medicine [injected into the joint] reacted negatively to extreme weather temperatures?

--
communicated by:
Joshua A Rogers
EpiCore Global Surveillance Project
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-mail thanks Joshua Rogers for his comments and the many other Epicore Global Surveillance Project members who responded with information. We await more information regarding the adverse reactions noted in the initial posting.

Most recalls of food or medications related to contamination by microbes are not reported by ProMED-mail unless human infections result, except for botulism because of the substantial health risk.

Lai and colleagues [1] have reported on human infections caused by unusual _Methylobacterium_ species. All 5 of the 6 infections were hospital-acquired and were intravenous catheter-related (the community-acquired infection was thought to be a primary bacteremia) and all had a favorable outcome. Two of the 6 including the community-acquired isolate were identified as _M. thiocyanatum_. A 2nd single case report of _M. thiocyanatum_ human infection was found in the Spanish literature [2] and was also related to an intravenous catheter.

1. Lai C-C, Cheng A, Liu W-L, et al. Infections caused by unusual Methylobacterium species. J Clin Microbiol. 2011;49: 3329-3331.
2. Garcia-Lozano T, Lerente Alegre P, Juan Banon JL, Aznar Oroval E. First case in Spain of bacteremia by _Methylobacterium thiocyanatum_ from Hickmann catheter in an immunosuppressed patient with Hodgkin's lymphoma. Med Clin (Barc). 2012;139: 602-603. - Mod.LL

